article.headline: Wright's 24 points, 10 boards lead Boilermakers
article.linkText: No. 10 Purdue hands No. 6 Minnesota its first loss
article.story:
WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- As coach of the only undefeated
women's basketball team in the country, Minnesota's Pam Borton
could sense the expectations weighing on her players.

Borton and her team no longer have to worry about that burden.

Shereka Wright had 24 points and 10 rebounds, helping No. 9
Purdue to a 65-56 victory over previously unbeaten No. 6 Minnesota
on Sunday.

The Gophers (15-1, 4-1 Big Ten) entered the game as the only
undefeated team in Division I, but they couldn't come up with the
big shots or big stops against Purdue (14-2, 4-1).

Local fans had rallied around the Gophers as they climbed in the
rankings, and that enthusiasm reached a fever pitch in a sellout
last Sunday against Iowa.

"I'm sure it kind of got to them in the last two to three
days," Borton said. "Back in the Twin Cities, that's all
everybody was talking about."

A large contingent of fans made the trip to West Lafayette,
where they watched Minnesota get outhustled and overcome by a
hungry Purdue team.

"That was the whole game -- second shots, loose balls, hustle
plays," Borton said. "They were the most aggressive team and the
most physical team out there."

Gophers' guard Lindsay Whalen was the focus of much of that
aggression.

The Boilermakers frustrated the nation's second-leading scorer,
who was averaging 23 points, for most of the game. A late surge
helped her finish with 16 points on 6-of-13 shooting.

Purdue doubled Whalen on most possessions and contested nearly
every shot, forcing her to commit nine turnovers. When she was
taken out of the game with just over eight minutes left, Whalen
pounded her chair in frustration before sitting down.

"The shots weren't falling in the beginning and I never really
got it going today," Whalen said.

Janel McCarville tried to step in while Whalen struggled during
the first 30 minutes. McCarville had 18 points and nine rebounds,
dominating the smaller Purdue front line.

"We needed to rely on her because Lindsay was struggling,"
Borton said.

But McCarville got into foul trouble midway through the second
half, and Purdue took advantage, attacking the inside and getting
to the foul line. McCarville fouled out with 1:53 to play.

The Boilermakers were aggressive from the opening tip, charging
to a 17-6 lead. They never let up, even through several Minnesota
comeback tries.

"Our kids were aggressive, we came out punching," Purdue coach
Kristy Curry said. "Minnesota has a great basketball team, but our
kids think we do, as well."

Purdue overcame 33 percent shooting by making 34-of-41 free
throws, including 20-of-24 in the second half. Minnesota shot
7-for-12 from the line.

Wright scored eight of her points in the final 3:30, when the
Gophers were trying to get back into the game.

"Being aggressive helped me get the opportunities at the free
throw line," said Wright, who shot 12-for-13 from the line.
"Everybody was aggressive going to the basket. We needed to be to
win."

Whalen hit consecutive drives, then found Shannon Schonrock for
a 3-pointer that pulled the Gophers within 53-50 with 3:09 to play.

Wright answered with four free throws and a pair of drives to
push the lead to 61-54 with 1:27 to play.

Katie Gearlds had 11 points, and Emily Heikes added eight points
and nine rebounds for Purdue, which won its fifth straight.

Purdue players and coaches said they hope giving Minnesota its
first loss brings some respect.

"It was just us proving a point," Wright said. "We're just as
good as any team in this conference."
